result.execSummary:
The defendant Jennifer A. Komp was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Bail Jumping-Felony, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).
  • Retail Theft - Intentionally Take (<=$500), a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.50(1m)(b).
  • Possession of Methamphetamine [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(g).
  • Neglecting a Child, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 948.21(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

(Case called at 2:15 PM) 
Defendant Jennifer A. Komp appears in custody with Attorney Francis Rivard.  Deputy District Attorney Peter J. Rindal appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
State outlines joint sentence recommendation for the Court.  State in compliance with victim notification requirements.  Parties agree that the Defendant has completed the probation term in Count 2 and that a sentence does not need to be ordered on that count.  Counsel make a record regarding sentence credit- Defense to file a stipulation and order if 45 additional days are to be counted.  Counsel make comments regarding the joint agreement.  Defendant makes a statement.  Court orders 18 months initial confinement and 18 months extended supervision on Count 1, concurrent to Dunn County case 16CF104; 18 months initial confinement and 18 months extended supervision on Count 8, concurrent to Count 1 and Dunn County case 16CF104; and 9 months jail ordered on Count 10 (concurrent as well).  Court orders court costs only on Count 2- Defense requests the Court not order that as she was formally discharged on that count- Court waives court costs on Count 2.  Conditions of extended supervision are as follows: Maintain absolute sobriety (no alcohol, no entry into any bars, taverns, or liquor stores, no illegal drugs, non-prescribed drugs, or drug paraphernalia).  No contact with any known drug dealers/users except in a therapeutic setting.  Comply with any conditions/assessments per agent.  396 days sentence credit ordered (to be adjusted if Counsel submit stipulation and order in writing).  Court makes ruling regarding prison programming eligibility (Clerk bases eligibility off of revocation packet from DOC).
